Keep kinetic fling (momentum) alive across main-thread jank stalls.

Device-confirmed root cause of "lag spikes kill scroll inertia" on heavy
pages (reddit): ScrollAnimationKinetic ends the fling when the per-tick offset
moves <1px, which assumes regular frame spacing. After a main-thread jank stall
the scrolling thread fires a catch-up displayDidRefresh tick immediately
(dt ~0.2ms); at near-zero dt the offset barely changes regardless of velocity,
so that test wrongly concluded the fling had stopped and killed it mid-flight
(instrumented: fling ended at ~2000 px/s right after a 217ms stall + a 0.2ms
tick). A controlled repro (numbered page + injected 200ms/350ms busy-loop)
showed coast halved, ~1500px -> ~750px.

Fix: only trust the per-tick "moved <1px" stop-test over a real frame interval
(dt >= 4ms); for abnormally short ticks rely on the dt-independent velocity
test (|v|<1) instead. Applies on top of webkit-kinetic-decel-friction-env.patch.
--- a/Source/WebCore/platform/ScrollAnimationKinetic.cpp
+++ b/Source/WebCore/platform/ScrollAnimationKinetic.cpp
@@ -123,7 +123,18 @@
         m_offset = m_upper;
     }
 
-    if (std::abs(m_velocity) < 1 || (lastTime > 0_s && std::abs(m_offset - lastOffset) < 1)) {
+    // The second test ("moved less than 1px since the last tick") is meant to
+    // detect that the fling has effectively stopped. But it assumes regular frame
+    // spacing: a tick with an abnormally small dt moves sub-pixel by definition,
+    // regardless of velocity. After a main-thread jank stall the scrolling thread
+    // fires a catch-up tick immediately (dt ~0.2ms) — its sub-pixel delta would
+    // wrongly end the fling mid-flight (observed: killed at ~2000px/s right after
+    // a 217ms stall). Only trust the per-tick delta over a real frame interval;
+    // otherwise rely on the dt-independent velocity test. (4ms is well under one
+    // 60Hz frame yet far above a clustered catch-up tick.)
+    auto tickInterval = m_elapsedTime - lastTime;
+    bool movedTooLittle = lastTime > 0_s && tickInterval >= 4_ms && std::abs(m_offset - lastOffset) < 1;
+    if (std::abs(m_velocity) < 1 || movedTooLittle) {
         m_offset = round(m_offset);
         m_velocity = 0;
     }
